      </div>
	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0393">393<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-02/ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0393.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div id="PJA02d108" class="doc letter">

    <h1>From James Warren</h1>
    
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="opener">
      <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My Dr. Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Plymo. Feby. 20th 1775</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
     </div>
     <p>I need not tell you that I was greatly disappointed and Chagrind at not seeing you at Cambridge A Member of our Congress. If it was the Choice of your Town, I Know not how they can Excuse, or even Extenuate the fault, surely A small degree of Patriotism would have dictated a very different Conduct. My disappointment was Encreased by not haveing the pleasure of seeing you on my way there, or return here. As matters are I am to Content myself for the present with my share in those valuable publications I have the pleasure of read-<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0394">[394<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-02/ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0394.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>ing every week in the Papers and no small pleasure it is to me to Consider my perticular Friend Advanceing (passibus Aequis)<a class="ptr" href="#PJA02d108n1" id="PJA02d108n1-ptr">1</a> his Countrys Interest and his own honour by Exposeing to publick view (with A nervous Eloquence) the Arts and wickedness of our Enemies and Asserting by derisive Arguments the rights of his Country. May the Applauses of the present and the Blessings of future Generations (A much better reward to A vertuous mind than pensions, and Salaries) United with the Goodness of his own heart; still Animate into Exertion those great Abilities which God in his Mercy has bestowed for the Advantage of this Country.</p>
     <p>I supposed our Congress would have Adjourned the day I left them, but it seems they found means to prolong the Sessions, A few days without haveing in view any Apparent Advantage that I could Conceive off. However I hope some good will come of it. I was concerned before I came away that we had then spent 10 days about what might have been Effected in four and perhaps as well. They Appeared to me to be dwindling into A School for debate, and Criticism rather than to Appear As A great Assembly to resolve and Act. A Certain Lady of your Acquaintance is much Concerned at hearing it is reported that She wrote the Group.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA02d108n2" id="PJA02d108n2-ptr">2</a> Parson Howe<a class="ptr" href="#PJA02d108n3" id="PJA02d108n3-ptr">3</a> told A large Company at Table that She was the Author of it. If this was true how came he by his Information, would A Certain friend of our have so little descretion as to Communicate such A matter to his Parson if he knew and much less if he only Conjectured it. Do speak to him About it, if he has set his parson A prateing, he ought to stop him. We have no Arrivals, no News. Our Military Gentry remain in statu quo at the Councellors Mansion House at Marshfield.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA02d108n4" id="PJA02d108n4-ptr">4</a> No Body but the Tories there and here take any Notice of them. Mrs. Warren Joins in Compliments to your Good Lady &amp;c.</p>
     <div class="closer">
      <p class="salute">I Am Your Sincere Friend and Humbl. Servt.,</p>
      <p class="signed">Jas. Warren</p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div class="docback">
     <div class="note-source" id="PJA02d108sn1">
      
   <p>
       <span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); addressed: To The Honbl. John Adams Esqr. att Braintree.</span>
      </p>

     </div>
     <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA02d108n1-ptr" id="PJA02d108n1">1</a>
      
   <p>By equal steps.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA02d108n2-ptr" id="PJA02d108n2">2</a>
      
   <p>Mercy Warren was very reluctant to have her authorship of <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">The Group</span> become widely known. See her letter to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Abigail Adams (17441818), m. John Adams 1764 ]">AA</abbr>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-01-02-0123" class="document">25 Feb. 1775</a>, <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Adams Family Correspondence&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield and others, Cambridge, 1963. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Adams Family Correspondence</span></span>, 1:187188.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA02d108n3-ptr" id="PJA02d108n3">3</a>
      
   <p>Rev. Joseph Howe (17471775), a Yale graduate and, at the time of this letter, pastor of the New South Church in Boston (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William B. Sprague, &lt;i&gt;Annals of the American Pulpit; or Commemorative&lt;/i&gt; Notices &lt;i&gt;of Distinguished American Clergymen of Various Denominations&lt;/i&gt;, New York, 18571869; 9 vols. ]">Sprague, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Annals Amer. Pulpit</span></span>, 1:707709).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA02d108n4-ptr" id="PJA02d108n4">4</a>
      
   <p>Loyalists in the towns of Marshfield and Scituate joined an association proposed by Timothy Ruggles in Dec. 1774 to oppose the actions of illegal Assemblies such as the Continental Congress and the Provincial Congress (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Boston Evening-Post</span>, 26 Dec. 1774; 30 Jan., 6 March 1775). On 17 and 18 Jan. the loyalists petitioned Gen. Gage for assistance and protection against local whigs and were sent one hundred <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0395">[395<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-02/ADMS-06-02-02-pb-0395.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>troops and an armed cutter for that purpose (same, 30 Jan.; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Correspondence of General Thomas Gage with the Secretaries of State,&lt;/i&gt; 17631775, ed. Clarence E. Carter, New Haven, 19311933; 2 vols. ]">Gage, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Corr.</span></span>, 1:391). The whigs ignored these moves, asserting that the loyalists fears were groundless.</p>

      
   <p>The Councellors Mansion House was the home of N. Ray Thomas, a mandamus councilor, the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Evening-Post</span> reporting that the troops were billeted at <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Mandamus</span> Thomass and at or near <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Tory</span> Whites (probably Abijah or Daniel White of Marshfield) inn and tavern (30 Jan. 1775; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Langdon Sibley and Clifford K. Shipton, &lt;i&gt;Biographical Sketches of Graduates of Harvard University, in Cambridge, Massachusetts&lt;/i&gt;, Cambridge and Boston, 1873. ]">Sibley-Shipton, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Harvard Graduates</span></span>, 13:136142; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Lorenzo Sabine, &lt;i&gt;Biographical Sketches of Loyalists of the American Revolution, with an Historical Essay&lt;/i&gt;, Boston, 1864; 2 vols. ]">Sabine, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">American Loyalists</span></span>, 2:419420). On 15 Feb. 1775 the Second Provincial Congress condemned the action of Gage and the loyalists and commended the local committees for their defense of liberty (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Lincoln, ed., &lt;i&gt;The Journals of Each Provincial Congress of Massachusetts in 1774 and&lt;/i&gt; 1775, &lt;i&gt;and of the Committee of Safety&lt;/i&gt;, Boston, 1838. ]">Mass. Provincial Congress, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Jours.</span></span>, p. 103104).</p>

     </div>
    </div>
